{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487194"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"274"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/274"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.02,0.74,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49793"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 20-year-old woman presents with a three day history of creamy white vaginal discharge associated with vulval and vaginal itch and irritation.\u00a0This is the first time she has had these symptoms and she is not pregnant. She has tried using more soap to wash herself, but this has not lessened her symptoms. She is currently sexually active and uses the combined oral contraceptive pill for contraception. Her last menstrual period was one week ago. On examination, the vulva is oedematous and inflamed in appearance and there is a thick white \u0022cottage cheese\u0022 discharge present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following management approaches is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical steroid, encourage less soap use and review in 3 days","Topical anti-fungal, encourage more soap use and review in 3 days","Vaginal swab, topical steroid, and review after results come back","Vaginal swab, topical anti-fungal, and review after results come back","Topical anti-fungal and topical steroid and review in 7 days"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation of cottage cheese-like discharge and vulvovaginal irritation is consistent with a diagnosis of candidal vulvovaginitis. Vulvovaginitis is reportedly more common in women who are sexually active, however there is no conclusive evidence that it is transmitted this way. Relevant risk factors for candida vulvovaginitis include pregnancy, immunosuppression, antibiotics, steroids, excessive washing of the genitals with soap and oestrogen use (such as the combined oral contraceptive pill).\u00a0Confirmation of the diagnosis is made on a saline wet mount of the swab, with pseudohyphae and spores visible. The treatment is with \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-fungal therapy\u003C/strong\u003E - topical intravaginal preparations are readily available over-the-counter, or a single oral dose of fluconazole may be used. Topical and oral treatments have equal efficacy in the treatment of uncomplicated vulvovaginal candidiasis. Whilst a swab isn\u0027t necessary, it is often performed in general practice to confirm the diagnosis and exclude other concurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E have no role in the management of candidal vulvovaginitis unless there is severe excoriation or itching, where they are used only for symptom relief and not management of the infection, as they can transiently worsen infection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn vulvovaginitis it is recommended to \u003Cstrong\u003Eavoid soaps\u003C/strong\u003E as these can cause irritation to the sensitive skin and can lead to non-infectious vulvovaginitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal swab, topical steroid, and review after results come back\u003C/strong\u003E would be an incorrect answer as the diagnosis is most often a clinical diagnosis and treatment should be initiated early to resolve symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical anti-fungal therapy is sufficient treatment for vulvovaginal candidiasis."],"references":["Lopez JEM. Candidiasis (vulvovaginal) BMJ Clin Evid 2015; 03:815."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"274"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98174"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T19:32:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T19:33:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated